post_cb({"3653674": {"ParentId": "3652182", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>Depending on the compiler, you may be able to use a void main function, however the proper way (that a truly standard compliant compiler should follow) is to return int with 0 being a nice &amp; clean exit and anything else indicating that your program has done something wrong.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "372743", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "3653674", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T18:44:07.190", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-06T18:44:07.190"}, "3652879": {"ParentId": "3652182", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<pre><code>But doesn't OS require int type value returned to specify whether program \nended well or not?\n</code></pre>\n<p>Why would it always? On windows when you double click on the icon, the process dies after it ends. OS do not check for the return type there. Even on linux if you just run the binary as ./runBinary, it simply runs and exits. The OS do not show message by itself that it fails or succeeds. </p>\n<p>All the above answers are right that the standard says it is int, but some compilers allow void too. </p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "439578", "LastEditorUserId": "445131", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-24T18:28:29.063", "Id": "3652879", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T16:16:29.627", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-24T18:28:29.063"}, "3652210": {"ParentId": "3652182", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p><code>main</code> returning <code>void</code> is accepted for backwards compatibility, but it is not legal. </p>\n<p>In this case, the exit code will be 0. You can still change the exit code, using exit function.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "83153", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "3652210", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T14:27:20.710", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-06T14:27:20.710"}, "3652279": {"ParentId": "3652182", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>In languages where a <code>void</code> return from main is legal (not C++), the OS usually sees a return value of <code>0</code> on normal (non-exceptional) program termination.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "59379", "LastEditorUserId": "59379", "LastEditDate": "2013-02-13T14:21:59.720", "Id": "3652279", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T14:37:44.577", "LastActivityDate": "2013-02-13T14:21:59.720"}, "3652206": {"ParentId": "3652182", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>C++ does <em>not</em> allow <code>main</code> to have a <code>void</code> return type. The published C++ standard requires it to be <code>int</code>. Some C++ compilers allow you to use <code>void</code>, but that's not recommended. In general, the OS doesn't care one way or the other. A specific OS might require a program to give a return value, but it doesn't necessarily have to come from <code>main</code>'s return value. If the C++ compiler allows <code>void</code>, then it probably provides some other means of specifying the program's exit code.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "33732", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "3652206", "Score": "26", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T14:26:29.937", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-06T14:26:29.937"}, "3652205": {"ParentId": "3652182", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>The C++ standard does not allow main() to have a return type of void. Most compilers will let it pass for historical reasons, though.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "71141", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "3652205", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T14:26:24.167", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-06T14:26:24.167"}, "3652182": {"CommentCount": "5", "ViewCount": "5512", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "445131", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T14:23:03.013", "LastActivityDate": "2013-09-24T18:28:29.063", "Title": "C++ void return type of main()", "AcceptedAnswerId": "3652206", "LastEditDate": "2013-09-24T18:22:06.423", "Id": "3652182", "Score": "11", "Body": "<p>Some C++ compilers allow the main function to have return type <code>void</code>.  But doesn't the Operating System require <code>int</code> type value returned to specify whether the program ended well or not?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++>", "OwnerUserId": "307797", "AnswerCount": "8"}, "3652214": {"ParentId": "3652182", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_3652182_3652214_0\">C++ allows main function to have return type void</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>No, it doesn't.</strong></p>\n<p>The C++ standard only requires 2 different types of main signatures.  Others may be optionally added if the return type is <code>int</code>.</p>\n<p>Implementations of C++ which allow void return types are incorrect in terms of  the C++ standard. </p>\n<p><em>C++03 standard S. 3.6.1-2:</em></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_3652182_3652214_1\">An implementation shall not predefine the main function. \n  This function shall not be overloaded. It shall\n  have a return type of type int, but otherwise its type is implementation-defined.\n  All implementations shall allow both\n  of the following definitions of main:  </p>\n<pre><code>int main() { /* ... */ } \nint main(int argc, char* argv[]) {/* ... */ }\n</code></pre>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If you want portable C++ code, or to write good C++ examples then you should always use one of the 2 variations above.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "3153", "LastEditorUserId": "32688", "LastEditDate": "2010-09-06T17:29:26.723", "Id": "3652214", "Score": "19", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T14:27:43.330", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-06T17:29:26.723"}, "3652234": {"ParentId": "3652182", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>That's why void main() is not allowed by standard C++ - though some compilers (e.g. gcc) does allow it.</p>\n<p>To make it short: always use int main(), never void main().</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "435816", "LastEditorUserId": "4023", "LastEditDate": "2010-09-06T16:03:00.580", "Id": "3652234", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2010-09-06T14:30:42.113", "LastActivityDate": "2010-09-06T16:03:00.580"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_3652182_3652214_0": {"section_id": 7146, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "length": 5}, "so_3652182_3652214_1": {"section_id": 7146, "quality": 0.75, "length": 18}}, "n3337": {"so_3652182_3652214_0": {"section_id": 6890, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "length": 5}, "so_3652182_3652214_1": {"section_id": 6890, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 22}}, "n4659": {"so_3652182_3652214_0": {"section_id": 8647, "quality": 0.7142857142857143, "length": 5}, "so_3652182_3652214_1": {"section_id": 8647, "quality": 0.75, "length": 18}}}});